Telkom Kenya CEO Mugo Kibati. PHOTO | SILA KIPLAGAT | NMG Telkom has partnered with Buy-Now-Pay-Later company Lipa Later to enable Kenyans to access smartphones through credit The agreement seeks to increase smartphone penetration in the country to boost users' incomes through the digital economy.  Through this partnership, consumers will be able to access select phones from brands such as iPhone, Nokia, Oppo, Realme, Tecno, Ulefone, Vivo, Xiaomi, Huawei, Bontel and Itel.  Lipa Later CEO Eric Muli said consumers will be able to get mobile gadgets on credits at Telkom stores in less than five minutes after signing up onto the platform with up to 12 monthly installments. “We are delighted to kick start this partnership with Telkom that will enable both our customers to get and stay connected by acquiring mobile and data devices affordably, "Additionally with our integration with UzaPoint, the process at the checkout till will be seamless for the consumer across all the Telkom outlets in the country,” Mr Muli said. Kenyans rely on digital tools and services to run online businesses, according to latest data by Dalberg, highlight the importance of smartphones. The Communication Authority of Kenya (CA) quarterly sector statistics ending September 2021, showed that Kenya has over 26 million smartphone devices out of 59 million mobile phone devices connected to mobile networks in the country, putting penetration levels at 53.4 percent.  “Telkom is excited to announce this partnership as it speaks to our belief that access to Mobile Data is a fundamental human right, "This is due to its strategic potential to progressively address digital inclusion; ensuring the benefits of the Internet and digital technologies are available to more Kenyans, consequently empowering the digital economy,” TelKom Chief Executive Mugo Kibati. kvnrotich@gmail.com